description.narrative:
•	Status of by-laws enabling implementation of the Energy Efficiency Law (prepared for approval); 
•	50 officials trained (including 15 women); 
•	Status of system of compliance checks and enforcement of performance standard for selected EE/RE products (Final version approved by decision-makers);
•	At least 2,000 green loans approved for SWH and other targeted EE/RE products; 
•	At least 16,000 beneficiaries using RE, including 10,000 women; 
•	350 kW Installed new RE-power generation capacity based on RESCO model, 
•	20 SWH systems facilitated by the project; 
•	4,000 people with improved access to energy (including 60% of women); 
•	Number of people accessed by marketing and awareness raising campaign (including percentage of women);

comment.narrative:
•	Lack of specific policies and regulations mandating or promoting wider adoption of EE/RE technologies by end-users;
•	Insufficient capacities among public agencies, to design and implement the required policies and regulations; 
•	Limited knowledge and awareness; 
•	No feasible green loans products existed and practiced in MFIs; 
•	Low ability to pay and unattractive financing terms for GE;
•	Lack of public financial incentives and mechanisms (grants, concessional loans, leasing) for RES/ EE products and technologies;
•	Low financial and technical capacity among MFIs on structuring SGES loans; 
•	High up-front costs of most EE/RE technologies, which are prohibitively expensive for consumers due to widespread poverty; 
•	Low participation of private actors in the Tajikistan energy service market;

Detailed policy and regulatory gap analysis, benchmarking and identification of priority policy and regulatory measures, such as building energy codes (SNIP), public procurement rules, etc., undertaken.
Stakeholder consultations conducted, including both relevant public authorities and business representatives regarding the scope and modalities of proposed policy and regulatory amendments.
Comprehensive market assessment on RES/ EE technologies done and report generated; 
Detailed evaluation criteria and requirements elaborated for selection of potential micro-finance institutions and evaluation of MFIs; Development of micro-credit schemes and financial products for RES/ Green Energy technologies; 

Community energy needs assessment (countrywide) carried out in project command zones and comprehensive report is produced
Terms of Reference prepared for Technical and Economic Feasibility Study with subsequent installation of solar systems in Murgab, GBAO. Bidding procedures finalized. Works will begin in January 2020 and be completed as of June 2020;
